        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I don't entirely agree. Even though explicitly set by the user, the files contain data: the words that should be ignored. It does not configure Nvim and is not even hand-written by a user. Even more so for the (binary) `.spl` files.\n\nI can't find it in the current version of the XDG spec, but the data directory was _meant_ to contain files that user may want to backup. Files that are definitely not meant to be included in a backup, should go in state or cache.\n\nHowever, the XDG spec is pretty vague about which directory should contain what type of files, and the lines between configuration, data, and state files are pretty thin. To me, a word list that is generated and modified by Nvim feels more like data than configuration.\n\n---\n\nOn another note, would this be considered for implementation, what would be the best approach: Just default `'spellfile'` to `$XDG_DATA_HOME .. 'spell/{spelllang}.{encoding}.add'`, or modify it in source (spellfile.c?)?\n\nThe pro's for setting `'spellfile'` are that it's simple to implement, easier to patch spellfile.c source from Vim, and clear to the user. The cons are that if `'spellfile'` is unset, the current default behaviour is that Nvim sets the filename based on the first lang in `'spelllang'`. I'm not sure if that's possible by just setting `'spellfile'` to a default value.",
