        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> (As long as both directories are searched, people can still decide for themselves by moving files manually.)\n\nI don't think I understand, as the directories are not really 'searched'. They are just checked to find the first writable directory, and than it is used. Thus either:\n\n1. `'spellfile'` is not set, and will be set to `rtp[0]/spell/{spelllang}.{encoding}.add` by Nvim upon first usage, e.g. after `zg` the value of `'spellfile'` is `/Users/yochem/.config/nvim/spell/en.utf-8.add`.\n2. `'spellfile'` is set: can be either one file or a list of files. These will be used.\n\nThis means that this would be a breaking change: if users did not set `'spellfile'` before and rely on the first rtp path being consistent, this would break if the default behaviour is changed to have stdpath('data') as default. They would need to either move their spell files accordingly, or set `'spellfile'` explicitly to their location (e.g. config).",
